text: I think the first trailer was a lot better. The more that was shown of teenagers being idiots and getting killed, the more  skeptical i became. On the bright side, the camerawork and visual style looks great and the effects look solid. Maybe it will hold out, but I've said it before and I'll say it again. Horror is one of the hardest genre's to make a good movie in. I'm all for somebody making a good found footage movie because they way I see it the sub-genre has a lot of promise when done right, but since its super cheap to do and any idiot with a camera thinks they can do a good found footage horror movie it dilutes the quality of these types of films substantially. I really want a good horror movie, but every year, 99% of those horror movies are shit and you're lucky if you get one trailer that looks promising and then with the good trailers, you're lucky if the film ends up being good.¬†  So far even with everybody complaining, this is still the most promising horror trailer released so far this year ( the first teaser is arguably better though) with Sinister 2 being number 2. So unless another horror trailer comes out that looks more promising this is one of the few prospects for a good horror film this year.

text: I personally am going to see this movie when it comes out.¬† If they do a sequel, I hope they explore the origin of Charlie and why he remains at the school after all these years.¬† I believe Charlie was a theatre kid who dreamed about becoming a movie someday and immortalizing himself on the big screen.¬† Bullied and made fun of by the popular kids of the school, Charlie gets even by ratting them out to the principle (they had marijuana on them and they could get expelled from school).¬† As the school prepares their local production of The Gallows, the cool¬†kids learn¬†that Charlie is going to play the lead role in the¬†play.¬† Wanting¬†revenge¬†on Charlie for ratting them out, they device a plan to embarrass Charlie in front of the whole school, they switch rope for the hanging scene with a cheaper rope.¬† For once they "hang" Charlie, it snaps and causes Charlie to fall right on his face.¬† As they prepare to do the deed, they accidently use the wrong¬†rope and¬†use a stronger brand of rope for the¬†hanging.¬† As they watch from the¬†back, they are unaware of what's going to happen¬†next.¬† Charlie is¬†hung from the¬†Gallows but the rest of the¬†cast sees that¬†this is not apart of the show, and¬†soon realizes he is dead.¬† Afraid of¬†getting into trouble and ruining their futures, they say¬†nothing and swore to secrecy.¬† This could lead to the storyline of the sequel, where they return to the high school for a reunion.¬† Now rich and successful¬†they are¬†completely unaware that Charlie hasn't forgotten about what they did to him, he has waited for over twenty years for his revenge.¬† They ended his life, now it's time to end theirs.

text: The song is by Think up Anger ft. Malia J but you can only hear it on YouTube. Just a side note for those complaining about being sick of the found footage movies; this movie was actually shot in 2011 on a very very low budget with a 7 person crew. They actually didn't even have a script, just an outline to follow and the actors basically improvd every scene. It's actually very interesting if you watch the interviews with the directors, they never expected anything to come of it but they cut a trailer and after a few very large production companies took interest they were given further funding to rework the movie and add to it and then it was screened and picked up by distributors for wide release. I would say with that in mind they did a way better job then a lot of big budget overdone "found footage" movies I've seen, and it has far more context to the story line then most where they just throw you into the action without any real backstory. It definitely starts out a little slow, but picks up speed as it goes and in my opinion kept you wanting more. Not to mention this was the first big project for these actors and considering they had no script, had to perform their own stunts and effects and basically had to come back later for reshoots and added scenes while still making it look authentic they did a damn good job.
author: Kristin Peterson

text: I'm getting tired of these trailers that barely show what's happening. From the looks of movies like "The Blair Witch Project" to "Insidious" to "Unfriended", these people seem to think they can get away with blurred photography, swift cutaways from the action and now this--red lighting. Sheesh! My eyesight is deteriorating with age and having to peer and squint at the screen to try to see actors (having most of them with their backs to the screen only means we don't care what happens to them, so not an effective storytelling ploy) and guess the action makes me irritated not scared. Here's hoping the actual movie relies on story rather than gore and cheap effects.

text: (Spoilers could be in this. You've been warned.) Went to the movies with a bunch of my friends to see this since it looked brilliant. Sadly, I couldn't believe that I had more laughs than jumpscares in this. The plot was intriguing, yes. But the thing they were lacking was horror. The only horror was the awful cover of 'Smells like Teen Spirit' in the trailer. They relied on jumpscares throughout the whole movie. The ending was a jumpscare which could easily be put in another scene because the climax was awesome until BAM! It's over? I didn't even flinch. (I do love my horror though, so I wasn't surprised.) It could've been executed better by adding more intensity. Plus, the trailer explained most of the story apart from the deaths which was pretty darn obvious that nearly all would be killed by Charlie. If you're thinking of watching this, I wouldn't spend my money going into the cinemas. Even my friend who was 'crapping their dacks' before it even started wasn't scared and they do not tolerate horror well. I do like the storyline of it though.
